>>35513426
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mammal#/media/File:Mammal_species_pie_chart.svg
Primates are eight percent of the overall animal population when not including humans (very rough estimate as it had no numbers other than the three largest groups being over seventy percent of all mammals). There are about four million primates not including humans. Chimpanzees make up approximately seven and a half percent of the population of the non-human primates. Using that as an estimate and considering that larger primates are typically smaller in number I decided that humans making up seven percent of the primate population, were all to have access to agriculture, civilization, and the population booms that come with that, would be a fairly reasonable estimate. So, with humans being seven percent of primates and primates being eight percent of mammals that puts humans at just over half a percent of the overall mammal population, or one in two hundred.
Do keep in mind, however, that this would not typically apply to individual countries as well as that this doesn't take into account the possibility that certain populations of animals that are a small portion now could skyrocket if they no longer had to worry about the natural order (e.g. deer and bunny populations not being kept down by wolves and foxes respectively).
